      "text": "Image metadata: Go\nWhy Go arrow_drop_down Press Enter to activate/deactivate dropdown\nCommon problems companies solve with Go\nStories about how and why companies use Go\nHow Go can help keep you secure by default\nLearn Press Enter to activate/deactivate dropdown\nDocs arrow_drop_down Press Enter to activate/deactivate dropdown\nThe official Go language specification\nA complete introduction to building software with Go\nStandard library\nReference documentation for Go's standard library\nLearn what's new in each Go release\nTips for writing clear, performant, and idiomatic Go code\nPackages Press Enter to activate/deactivate dropdown\nCommunity arrow_drop_down Press Enter to activate/deactivate dropdown\nVideos from prior events\nMeetups open_in_new\nMeet other local Go developers\nConferences open_in_new\nLearn and network with Go developers from around the world\nThe Go project's official blog.\nGet help and stay informed from Go\nImage metadata: Go.\nWhy Go navigate_next navigate_before Why Go\nDocs navigate_next navigate_before Docs\nStandard library\nCommunity navigate_next navigate_before Community\nMeetups open_in_new\nConferences open_in_new\nAndrew Gerrand 16 January 2013\nIf there’s one thing most people know about Go, is that it is designed for concurrency. No introduction to Go is complete without a demonstration of its goroutines and channels.",
